title: Resume Screening with Word Vectorizing and Cosine Similarity
text: Examined many interesting vectorization methods like scikit-learn, BERT, and Word2Vec. Handled pretty much all of the code writing, most of the difficulty in this project came from understanding how and what tools to use for BERT and Word2Vec. Completed for a 2023 fall capstone project, pdf of paper will be provided soon!

title: Robot Conversations about NBA Players with Microsoft Autogen
text: Used a group-chat dynamic, with a sentiment analysis agent (using tools for Reddit data), a statistician (using tools for basketball-reference data) and a third ‘Critic’ role to analyze player value. Partner handled basketball-reference data scraping and creating classes for each player, I handled getting comments from reddit API, conducting sentiment analysis and setting up Autogen. Link to our presentation can be found here: https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1MQmrhFRy8WjoMnQqr2iWDYENgmf2MIFrTpMnWnYKfLA/edit?usp=sharing. Link to google colab file here as well: https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1kf0T0eP569OdY5-dTM78m4ZJZ6aNBMP9?usp=sharing. We’re still tinkering with the model!

title: About Me: Professionally Speaking
text:
I’m Jack, recent graduate Software Engineer working on the on-premises migration integration team at CNA Insurance. I love to code and I care about the quality of the code I write. I’m looking to work on a team of developers who are serious about software done well.
I am also passionate about my Chinese studies and graduated with a double major in Chinese and CS. I spent the last two years of college conducting research on Chinese migrant worker poetry with the support of the Mellon Mays foundation.

Qualifications

Languages (Ordered)

Strong
Java: Java Standard Library, data structures  Python: Pandas, NumPy, Matplotlib


Decent
JS: Game systems, Phaser3  C: For dedicated parallel programming



TOOLS USED (ACADEMICALLY)
VSCode, PyCharm, Google Colab, Git, Linux/Bash


TOOLS USED (PROFESSIONALLY)
Guidewire, Gosu, Integration Gateway, Postman, DataDog, Git


My Interests / Academic Experience
Machine Learning: Applying learning models to a large-corpus of data such as random forest, gradient-boost, ADAboost. Experience with libraries such as SKLearn, Tensor-Flow, PyTorch and BERT.



Decision Tree Model with scikit-learn


Artificial Intelligence: Experience with Microsoft Autogen, experimenting with multiple AI agents. Applying three agent, group-chat dynamic to a conversation on NBA player value.
Parallel Programming: OpenMP / MPI / OpenACC parallezing in C using gcc and pgcc compilers.



Testing Data from Examining Different Scalability in Conway’s Game of Life


Chinese Language and Culture: I am fluent in Mandarin and have studied in Taiwan and mainland China. With the Mellon-Mays Fellowship I researched and translated 50 Chinese migrant worker poems and presented on this work as an undergrad student.


The Usual CS Coursework
Core Concepts in CS, Object Oriented Programming, Data Structures, Computer Systems, Software Development, Discrete Mathematics, Algorithm Design / Analysis, Parallel Programming and Intro to AI.


My coding Ethics/ Attitude
Enabling the team: When I write my code, I pay attention to who may need to read and understand my code, considering how I can provide psuedo-code and friendly variable names to make my code easy for others to utilize. I highly value communication with project mates.
Testing: When I build software, I think about the correctness of the code and I generate unit tests as I go to make the code resilient to future changes. As I have entered the professional world of coding, I especially like to emphasize this for scalability and efficiency.

title: Parallelizing a Forest Fire Simulation
text: Comparing pgcc multicore and openmp versions versus using kernel functions run on GPU. Solo project completed for a fall senior capstone. This project demonstrated just how much more efficiently this kind of simulation can be done using the manycore GPU.
